## Test Anti-Pattern Audit: `ProductCatalogTests.cs`

### Summary

**10 tests, 10 findings — 7 Critical, 3 High, 0 Medium**

This is a textbook **coverage-touching** test suite. Every public method on `ProductCatalog` is called (hence 95% coverage), but almost nothing is actually verified. These tests cannot fail when production logic breaks — which is exactly why bugs reach production.

---

### 🔴 Critical — Tests Giving False Confidence

#### 1. Coverage Touching (Systemic)
**All 10 tests, lines 17–89**

The entire class follows a pattern: call the method, maybe check `IsNotNull`, move on. This inflates coverage metrics while verifying zero behavior. 7 of 10 tests fall into the specific sub-patterns below.

---

#### 2. No Assertion — `AddProduct_Works` (line 17)
Calls `AddProduct` but never verifies the product was stored.

```csharp
// BEFORE (line 17-21)
public void AddProduct_Works()
{
    var product = new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 9.99m);
    _catalog.AddProduct(product);
}

// FIX
public void AddProduct_StoresProduct()
{
    var product = new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 9.99m);
    _catalog.AddProduct(product);
    var stored = _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001");
    Assert.AreEqual("Widget", stored?.Name);
    Assert.AreEqual(9.99m, stored?.Price);
}
```

#### 3. No Assertion — `UpdatePrice_Works` (line 33)
Calls `UpdatePrice` but never checks the price changed. A no-op implementation would pass.

```csharp
// FIX
public void UpdatePrice_UpdatesStoredPrice()
{
    _catalog.AddProduct(new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 9.99m));
    _catalog.UpdatePrice("SKU-001", 14.99m);
    var updated = _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001");
    Assert.AreEqual(14.99m, updated?.Price);
}
```

#### 4. No Assertion — `RemoveProduct_Works` (line 39)
Never checks the product was actually deleted.

```csharp
// FIX
public void RemoveProduct_ProductNoLongerExists()
{
    _catalog.AddProduct(new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 9.99m));
    _catalog.RemoveProduct("SKU-001");
    Assert.IsNull(_catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001"));
}
```

#### 5. No Assertion — `GetProductCount_Works` (line 63)
Calls `GetProductCount()` and discards the result entirely.

```csharp
// FIX
public void GetProductCount_ReturnsCorrectCount()
{
    Assert.AreEqual(0, _catalog.GetProductCount());
    _catalog.AddProduct(new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 9.99m));
    Assert.AreEqual(1, _catalog.GetProductCount());
